{"title_page": "Mike Olscamp", "text_new": "{{BLP sources|date=November 2010}}\n{{Infobox officeholder\n|image = <!-- only free-content images are allowed for depicting living people - see [[WP:NONFREE]] -->\n| name = Michael Olscamp\n| birth_place = [[Campbellton, New Brunswick]]\n| party = [[Progressive Conservative Party of New Brunswick|Progressive Conservative]]  \n| spouse = Karen\n| occupation = teacher, politician\n| assembly              = New Brunswick Legislative\n| constituency_AM       = [[Tantramar (electoral district)|Tantramar]]\n| term_start = September 18, 2006\n| term_end = September 27, 2014\n| predecessor = [[Peter Mesheau]]\n| successor = [[Bernard LeBlanc]]<ref>[[Memramcook-Tantramar]]</ref>\n| office1 = [[Department of Agriculture and Aquaculture (New Brunswick)|Minister of Agriculture, Aquaculture]] [[Department of Fisheries (New Brunswick)|and Fisheries]]\n| premier1 = [[David Alward]]\n| term_start1 = October 12, 2010 \n| term_end1 = October 7, 2014\n| predecessor1 = [[Ronald Ouellette]]<ref>(as minister of agriculture and aquaculture)</ref><br />[[Rick Doucet]]<ref>(as minister of fisheries)</ref>\n| successor1 =[[Rick Doucet]]\n}}\n\n'''Michael Robert Olscamp''' is a [[politician]] in the [[province (Canada)|province]] of [[New Brunswick]], Canada, and a retired teacher. He was elected to the [[Legislative Assembly of New Brunswick]] in the [[2006 New Brunswick general election|2006 election]] as the [[Progressive Conservative Party of New Brunswick|Progressive Conservative]] MLA for [[Tantramar (electoral district)|Tantramar]]. He did not win re-election in 2014.<ref>{{cite web|title= Mike Olscamp-Candidate for Memramcook-Tantramar|url= http://pcnb.ca/mike-olscamp-candidate-for-memramcook-tantramar/|publisher=PCNB|accessdate= 17 April 2015}}</ref>\n\n==Biography==\nHe graduated from Campbellton Composite High School and then achieved journeyman status as an electrician. In 1972\u201373, he enrolled in the Vocational Teacher Training Program at the New Brunswick Institute of Technology in [[Moncton]]. He then went on to earn a Bachelor of Education from the [[University of Moncton]].\n\nOlscamp taught vocational education at [[Tantramar Regional High School]] in Sackville. After teaching he was vice-principal of the high school in the 1980s. He was then recruited as Director of Inmate Programs at minimum security Westmorland Institution in [[Dorchester, New Brunswick|Dorchester]].\n\nHe decided to return to a career in the field of public education by teaching at Port Elgin Regional Memorial School for four years. He then returned to Tantramar Regional High School and taught French.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www1.gnb.ca/legis/bios1/bio-e.asp?idNo=139&version=e |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2010-04-15 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100106222740/http://www1.gnb.ca/legis/bios1/bio-e.asp?idNo=139&version=e |archivedate=2010-01-06 }} Bio of Mike Olscamp</ref>\n\nA sports enthusiast, Olscamp spent three decades coaching the Tantramar area youth. He coached basketball from the elementary through high school levels winning three provincial championships at the high school level. Prior to being elected to the Legislative Assembly of New Brunswick, he served as the assistant coach of the [[Mount Allison Mounties]] Men's basketball team.\n\nHe is married to Karen and has two sons, Andrew and William.\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{Alward Ministry}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Olscamp, Mike}}\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Canadian schoolteachers]]\n[[Category:Members of the Executive Council of New Brunswick]]\n[[Category:People from Campbellton, New Brunswick]]\n[[Category:Progressive Conservative Party of New Brunswick MLAs]]\n[[Category:21st-century Canadian politicians]]\n[[Category:U Sports coaches]]\n[[Category:Year of birth missing (living people)]]\n\n\n{{NewBrunswick-politician-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{BLP sources|date=November 2010}}\n{{Infobox officeholder\n|image = <!-- only free-content images are allowed for depicting living people - see [[WP:NONFREE]] -->\n| name = Michael Olscamp\n| birth_place = [[Campbellton, New Brunswick]]\n| party = [[Progressive Conservative Party of New Brunswick|Progressive Conservative]]  \n| spouse = Karen\n| occupation = teacher, politician\n| assembly              = New Brunswick Legislative\n| constituency_AM       = [[Tantramar (electoral district)|Tantramar]]\n| term_start = September 18, 2006\n| term_end = September 27, 2014\n| predecessor = [[Peter Mesheau]]\n| successor = [[Bernard LeBlanc]]<ref>[[Memramcook-Tantramar]]</ref>\n| office1 = [[Department of Agriculture and Aquaculture (New Brunswick)|Minister of Agriculture, Aquaculture]] [[Department of Fisheries (New Brunswick)|and Fisheries]]\n| premier1 = [[David Alward]]\n| term_start1 = October 12, 2010 \n| term_end1 = October 7, 2014\n| predecessor1 = [[Ronald Ouellette]]<ref>(as minister of agriculture and aquaculture)</ref><br />[[Rick Doucet]]<ref>(as minister of fisheries)</ref>\n| successor1 =[[Rick Doucet]]\n}}\n\n'''Michael Robert Olscamp''' is a [[politician]] in the [[province (Canada)|province]] of [[New Brunswick]], Canada, and a retired teacher. He was elected to the [[Legislative Assembly of New Brunswick]] in the [[2006 New Brunswick general election|2006 election]] as the [[Progressive Conservative Party of New Brunswick|Progressive Conservative]] MLA for [[Tantramar (electoral district)|Tantramar]]. He did not win re-election in 2014.<ref>{{cite web|title= Mike Olscamp-Candidate for Memramcook-Tantramar|url= http://pcnb.ca/mike-olscamp-candidate-for-memramcook-tantramar/|publisher=PCNB|accessdate= 17 April 2015}}</ref>\n\n==Biography==\nHe graduated from Campbellton Composite High School and then achieved journeyman status as an electrician. In 1972-73, he enrolled in the Vocational Teacher Training Program at the New Brunswick Institute of Technology in [[Moncton]]. He then went on to earn a Bachelor of Education from the [[University of Moncton]].\n\nOlscamp taught vocational education at [[Tantramar Regional High School]] in Sackville. After teaching he was vice-principal of the high school in the 1980s. He was then recruited as Director of Inmate Programs at minimum security Westmorland Institution in [[Dorchester, New Brunswick|Dorchester]].\n\nHe decided to return to a career in the field of public education by teaching at Port Elgin Regional Memorial School for four years. He then returned to Tantramar Regional High School and taught French.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www1.gnb.ca/legis/bios1/bio-e.asp?idNo=139&version=e |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2010-04-15 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100106222740/http://www1.gnb.ca/legis/bios1/bio-e.asp?idNo=139&version=e |archivedate=2010-01-06 }} Bio of Mike Olscamp</ref>\n\nA sports enthusiast, Olscamp spent three decades coaching the Tantramar area youth. He coached basketball from the elementary through high school levels winning three provincial championships at the high school level. Prior to being elected to the Legislative Assembly of New Brunswick, he served as the assistant coach of the [[Mount Allison Mounties]] Men\u2019s basketball team.\n\nHe is married to Karen and has two sons, Andrew and William.\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{Alward Ministry}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Olscamp, Mike}}\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Canadian schoolteachers]]\n[[Category:Members of the Executive Council of New Brunswick]]\n[[Category:People from Campbellton, New Brunswick]]\n[[Category:Progressive Conservative Party of New Brunswick MLAs]]\n[[Category:21st-century Canadian politicians]]\n[[Category:U Sports coaches]]\n[[Category:Year of birth missing (living people)]]\n\n\n{{NewBrunswick-politician-stub}}\n", "name_user": "Iridescent", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eBiography:Cleanup andtypo fixing,typo(s) fixed: \u2019s \u2192 's, 1972-73 \u2192 1972\u201373", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Mike_Olscamp"}
{"title_page": "Fred Magee", "text_new": "'''Fred Magee''' (May 29, 1875 \u2013 May 5, 1952) was an industrialist and political figure in [[New Brunswick]], Canada. He represented [[Westmorland County, New Brunswick|Westmorland County]] in the [[Legislative Assembly of New Brunswick]] from 1917\u201325.\n\n==Career==\nHe was born in [[Baie Verte, New Brunswick]], the son of Thomas and Olive (n\u00e9e Oulton) Magee, both of [[Ireland|Irish]] descent.<ref>[http://ourmaritimeties.com/tng/showmedia.php?mediaID=3437&medialinkID=6366 Genealogy, picture of headstone]</ref> He was educated in Baie Verte, [[Saint John, New Brunswick|Saint John]] and [[Fredericton, New Brunswick|Fredericton]] and went on to study at the [[University of New Brunswick]]. Following the family tradition, Fred, at age 22, opened a general store in Port Elgin. He was elected to and served on the Westmorland County council from 1908\u201310. He was a member of the province's Executive Council, first as [[minister without portfolio]] in 1921 and then president. Magee later operated produce and fish processing plants in [[Port Elgin, New Brunswick|Port Elgin]], selling lobster under the Mephisto label. He died in 1952, shortly before his 77th birthday. He had been married to Myrtle R. McLeod in 1899.<ref>Bill Hamilton, [http://www.billhamiltonflashback.ca/listnews.php?id=101&cid=1&searchtext=&offset=20 \"The Man Behind Mephisto: Fred magee - An Extraordinary Entrepreneur\"] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110721123944/http://www.billhamiltonflashback.ca/listnews.php?id=101&cid=1&searchtext=&offset=20 |date=2011-07-21 }}, Tantramar Flashback, 2002</ref>\n\nHis former home on Main Street in Port Elgin is now an apartment and the neighbouring building, his former offices, used to house the municipal office, fire department and library. Was sold Nov 1 2018 to Kerry Phibbs and Christina Morrison who plan to use part of the building as Port Elgin Community Hall.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.villageofportelgin.com/history.php |title=Village of Port Elgin History |access-date=2011-10-28 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110810172649/http://www.villageofportelgin.com/history.php |archive-date=2011-08-10 |url-status=dead }}</ref> In his will he left a large endowment to the [[University of New Brunswick]].\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Magee, Fred}}\n[[Category:1875 births]]\n[[Category:1952 deaths]]\n[[Category:Members of the Legislative Assembly of New Brunswick]]\n[[Category:Canadian businesspeople]]\n[[Category:People from Westmorland County, New Brunswick]]\n[[Category:Place of death missing]]\n[[Category:Members of the Executive Council of New Brunswick]]\n\n\n{{NewBrunswick-politician-stub}}\n", "text_old": "'''Fred Magee''' (May 29, 1875 \u2013 May 5, 1952) was an industrialist and political figure in [[New Brunswick]], Canada. He represented [[Westmorland County, New Brunswick|Westmorland County]] in the [[Legislative Assembly of New Brunswick]] from 1917-25.\n\n==Career==\nHe was born in [[Baie Verte, New Brunswick]], the son of Thomas and Olive (n\u00e9e Oulton) Magee, both of [[Ireland|Irish]] descent.<ref>[http://ourmaritimeties.com/tng/showmedia.php?mediaID=3437&medialinkID=6366 Genealogy, picture of headstone]</ref> He was educated in Baie Verte, [[Saint John, New Brunswick|Saint John]] and [[Fredericton, New Brunswick|Fredericton]] and went on to study at the [[University of New Brunswick]]. Following the family tradition, Fred, at age 22, opened a general store in Port Elgin. He was elected to and served on the Westmorland County council from 1908-10. He was a member of the province's Executive Council, first as [[minister without portfolio]] in 1921 and then president. Magee later operated produce and fish processing plants in [[Port Elgin, New Brunswick|Port Elgin]], selling lobster under the Mephisto label. He died in 1952, shortly before his 77th birthday. He had been married to Myrtle R. McLeod in 1899.<ref>Bill Hamilton, [http://www.billhamiltonflashback.ca/listnews.php?id=101&cid=1&searchtext=&offset=20 \"The Man Behind Mephisto: Fred magee - An Extraordinary Entrepreneur\"] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110721123944/http://www.billhamiltonflashback.ca/listnews.php?id=101&cid=1&searchtext=&offset=20 |date=2011-07-21 }}, Tantramar Flashback, 2002</ref>\n\nHis former home on Main Street in Port Elgin is now an apartment and the neighbouring building, his former offices, used to house the municipal office, fire department and library. Was sold Nov 1 2018 to Kerry Phibbs and Christina Morrison who plan to use part of the building as Port Elgin Community Hall.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.villageofportelgin.com/history.php |title=Village of Port Elgin History |access-date=2011-10-28 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110810172649/http://www.villageofportelgin.com/history.php |archive-date=2011-08-10 |url-status=dead }}</ref> In his will he left a large endowment to the [[University of New Brunswick]].\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Magee, Fred}}\n[[Category:1875 births]]\n[[Category:1952 deaths]]\n[[Category:Members of the Legislative Assembly of New Brunswick]]\n[[Category:Canadian businesspeople]]\n[[Category:People from Westmorland County, New Brunswick]]\n[[Category:Place of death missing]]\n[[Category:Members of the Executive Council of New Brunswick]]\n\n\n{{NewBrunswick-politician-stub}}\n", "name_user": "Iridescent", "label": "safe", "comment": "Cleanup andtypo fixing,typo(s) fixed: 1917-25 \u2192 1917\u201325 (2)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Fred_Magee"}
{"title_page": "Hugh Mackay (New Brunswick politician)", "text_new": "'''Hugh Mackay''' (ca 1751 &ndash; January 28, 1848) was a judge and political figure in [[New Brunswick]]. He represented Charlotte in the [[Legislative Assembly of New Brunswick]] from 1793 to 1795, from 1802 to 1809 and from 1817 to 1830.<ref name=\"Campbell\">{{cite book |url=https://archive.org/stream/scotsmanincanada01campuoft/scotsmanincanada01campuoft_djvu.txt |title=The Scotsman in Canada |year=1911 |last=Campbell |first=Wilfred |page=228}}</ref>\n\nMackay served in the loyalist forces during the [[American Revolution]], afterwards settling in [[St. George, New Brunswick]]. He served as a colonel in the militia there and was senior judge in the Court of  Common Pleas for [[Charlotte County, New Brunswick|Charlotte County]]. Mackay died at the age of 97.<ref name=\"Campbell\" />\n\nMilitary Service: [[Queen's Rangers]], May 21, 1778<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.carolana.com/NC/Revolution/loyalist_militia_roll_of_officers.html|title=Loyallist Militia Roll of Officers, Ensign Hugh MacKay|author=Lewis, J.D.|website=North Carolina in the American Revolution|accessdate=August 21, 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Death==\nHe died on January 28, 1848 in the [[Saint George Parish, New Brunswick|Parish of Saint George]] in the [[Charlotte County, New Brunswick|County of Charlotte and Province of New Brunswick]].  He was buried at the  St. Mark's Cemetery in St. George.  His tombstone epitaph reads:<ref name=\"Will\">{{cite web|url=http://carensecord.ca/locations/NewBrunswick/MacKay/MacKay_will.html|title=Will of Hugh MacKay|accessdate=August 21, 2019}}, Provincial Archives of New Brunswick, RS63, Charlotte County Probate, Film F11590, This is the will of Hugh MacKay of Bonny River, St. George Parish, Charlotte County.  The will is dated July 5, 1844.  He died on Jan. 28, 1848.</ref>\n\n\"Sacred to the Memory of Hugh MacKay Esq.<br/> \nLate of Suther Hall St. George.<br/>  \nWho Departed this Life 28th January A. D. 1848 in the 97th Year of his Age.<br/>  \nHe was a Native of Sutherlandshire Scotland.<br/>  \nServed during the American Revolutionary War as an Officer in the Queen\u2019s American Rangers Regiment of Foot.<br/>  \nAnd was for many Years Colonel of the Charlotte County Militia.<br/>  \nAnd was Leading Member in the House of Assembly of the Province for the said County.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://carensecord.ca/locations/NewBrunswick/MacKay/MacKay_will_background.html|title=Transcription of the will of Hugh MacKay|accessdate=August 21, 2019}}</ref><br/>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Mackay, Hugh}}\n[[Category:Year of birth uncertain]]\n[[Category:1848 deaths]]\n[[Category:Members of the Legislative Assembly of New Brunswick]]\n[[Category:Judges in New Brunswick]]\n[[Category:Colony of New Brunswick judges]]\n[[Category:Colony of New Brunswick people]]\n[[Category:United Empire Loyalists]]\n[[Category:Loyalist military personnel of the American Revolutionary War]]\n[[Category:American emigrants to pre-Confederation New Brunswick]]\n[[Category:Loyalists in the American Revolution from New York (state)]]\n\n\n{{NewBrunswick-politician-stub}}\n", "text_old": "'''Hugh Mackay''' (ca 1751 &ndash; January 28, 1848) was a judge and political figure in [[New Brunswick]]. He represented Charlotte in the [[Legislative Assembly of New Brunswick]] from 1793 to 1795, from 1802 to 1809 and from 1817 to 1830.<ref name=\"Campbell\">{{cite book |url=https://archive.org/stream/scotsmanincanada01campuoft/scotsmanincanada01campuoft_djvu.txt |title=The Scotsman in Canada |year=1911 |last=Campbell |first=Wilfred |page=228}}</ref>\n\nMackay served in the loyalist forces during the [[American Revolution]], afterwards settling in [[St. George, New Brunswick]]. He served as a colonel in the militia there and was senior judge in the Court of  Common Pleas for [[Charlotte County, New Brunswick|Charlotte County]]. Mackay died at the age of 97.<ref name=\"Campbell\" />\n\nMilitary Service: [[Queen's Rangers]], May 21, 1778<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.carolana.com/NC/Revolution/loyalist_militia_roll_of_officers.html|title=Loyallist Militia Roll of Officers, Ensign Hugh MacKay|author=Lewis, J.D.|website=North Carolina in the American Revolution|accessdate=August 21, 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Death==\nHe died on January 28, 1848 in the [[Saint George Parish, New Brunswick|Parish of Saint George]] in the [[Charlotte County, New Brunswick|County of Charlotte and Province of New Brunswick]].  He was buried at the  St. Mark\u2019s Cemetery in St. George.  His tombstone epitaph reads:<ref name=\"Will\">{{cite web|url=http://carensecord.ca/locations/NewBrunswick/MacKay/MacKay_will.html|title=Will of Hugh MacKay|accessdate=August 21, 2019}}, Provincial Archives of New Brunswick, RS63, Charlotte County Probate, Film F11590, This is the will of Hugh MacKay of Bonny River, St. George Parish, Charlotte County.  The will is dated July 5, 1844.  He died on Jan. 28, 1848.</ref>\n\n\"Sacred to the Memory of Hugh MacKay Esq.<br/> \nLate of Suther Hall St. George.<br/>  \nWho Departed this Life 28th January A. D. 1848 in the 97th Year of his Age.<br/>  \nHe was a Native of Sutherlandshire Scotland.<br/>  \nServed during the American Revolutionary War as an Officer in the Queen\u2019s American Rangers Regiment of Foot.<br/>  \nAnd was for many Years Colonel of the Charlotte County Militia.<br/>  \nAnd was Leading Member in the House of Assembly of the Province for the said County.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://carensecord.ca/locations/NewBrunswick/MacKay/MacKay_will_background.html|title=Transcription of the will of Hugh MacKay|accessdate=August 21, 2019}}</ref><br/>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Mackay, Hugh}}\n[[Category:Year of birth uncertain]]\n[[Category:1848 deaths]]\n[[Category:Members of the Legislative Assembly of New Brunswick]]\n[[Category:Judges in New Brunswick]]\n[[Category:C