{"title_page": "Rose-Marie Losier-Cool", "text_new": "{{Infobox officeholder\n| honorific-prefix = [[The Honourable]]\n| name             = Rose-Marie Losier-Cool\n| honorific-suffix = \n| image            = \n| imagesize        = \n| office           = [[Senate of Canada|Senator]] for [[Tracadie-Sheila, New Brunswick|Tracadie]], [[New Brunswick]]\n| appointed        = [[Jean Chr\u00e9tien]]\n| predecessor      =\n| successor        = \n| term_start       = March 21, 1995\n| term_end         = June 18, 2012\n| birth_date       = {{birth date and age|1937|6|18}}\n| birth_place      = [[Tracadie-Sheila, New Brunswick|Tracadie]], [[New Brunswick]]\n| death_date       =\n| death_place      =\n| nationality      =\n| spouse           =\n| party            = [[Liberal Party of Canada|Liberal]]\n| relations        =\n| children         =\n| residence        =\n| alma_mater       = \n| occupation       =\n| profession       =\n| cabinet          = \n| committees       =\n| portfolio        = \n| religion         =\n| signature        =\n| website          =\n| footnotes        =\n}}\n'''Rose-Marie Losier-Cool''' (born June 18, 1937) is a retired [[Senate of Canada|Canadian Senator]] for New Brunswick.\n\nA member of New Brunswick's [[Acadian]] community, Losier-Cool worked as a teacher for thirty-three years, two decades of which were spent at ''\u00c9cole secondaire N\u00e9pisiguit'' in [[Bathurst, New Brunswick]].\n\nShe was elected the first woman president of the ''Association des enseignantes et enseignants francophones du Nouveau-Brunswick'' in 1983 and has sat on the board of directors of the ''Canadian Teachers' Federation''. She was awarded the Teacher of the Year Award for non-sexist teaching by the government of New Brunswick in 1993. In 1994\u201395, she was Vice-President of the ''New Brunswick Advisory Council on the Status of Women''.\n\nLosier-Cool was appointed to the Senate on March 21, 1995 on the advice of then [[Prime Minister of Canada]] [[Jean Chr\u00e9tien]] and sits as a [[Liberal Party of Canada|Liberal]]. In January 2004, she was appointed Government [[parliamentary whip|Whip]] in the Senate, the first woman ever to hold this role. Loisier-Cool left the Senate upon reaching the mandatory retirement age of 75 on June 18, 2012.\n\n==External links==\n* {{Canadian Parliament links|ID=14040}}\n*[http://www.liberalsenateforum.ca/Senator/losier Liberal Senate Forum]\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Losier-Cool, Rose-Marie}}\n[[Category:1937 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Liberal Party of Canada senators]]\n[[Category:Canadian senators from New Brunswick]]\n[[Category:Canadian schoolteachers]]\n[[Category:Women members of the Senate of Canada]]\n[[Category:Women in New Brunswick politics]]\n[[Category:21st-century Canadian politicians]]\n[[Category:21st-century Canadian women politicians]]\n\n\n{{NewBrunswick-politician-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox officeholder\n| honorific-prefix = [[The Honourable]]\n| name             = Rose-Marie Losier-Cool\n| honorific-suffix = \n| image            = \n| imagesize        = \n| office           = [[Senate of Canada|Senator]] for [[Tracadie-Sheila, New Brunswick|Tracadie]], [[New Brunswick]]\n| appointed        = [[Jean Chr\u00e9tien]]\n| predecessor      =\n| successor        = \n| term_start       = March 21, 1995\n| term_end         = June 18, 2012\n| birth_date       = {{birth date and age|1937|6|18}}\n| birth_place      = [[Tracadie-Sheila, New Brunswick|Tracadie]], [[New Brunswick]]\n| death_date       =\n| death_place      =\n| nationality      =\n| spouse           =\n| party            = [[Liberal Party of Canada|Liberal]]\n| relations        =\n| children         =\n| residence        =\n| alma_mater       = \n| occupation       =\n| profession       =\n| cabinet          = \n| committees       =\n| portfolio        = \n| religion         =\n| signature        =\n| website          =\n| footnotes        =\n}}\n'''Rose-Marie Losier-Cool''' (born June 18, 1937) is a retired [[Senate of Canada|Canadian Senator]] for New Brunswick.\n\nA member of New Brunswick's [[Acadian]] community, Losier-Cool worked as a teacher for thirty-three years, two decades of which were spent at ''\u00c9cole secondaire N\u00e9pisiguit'' in [[Bathurst, New Brunswick]].\n\nShe was elected the first woman president of the ''Association des enseignantes et enseignants francophones du Nouveau-Brunswick'' in 1983 and has sat on the board of directors of the ''Canadian Teachers' Federation''. She was awarded the Teacher of the Year Award for non-sexist teaching by the government of New Brunswick in 1993. In 1994-95, she was Vice-President of the ''New Brunswick Advisory Council on the Status of Women''.\n\nLosier-Cool was appointed to the Senate on March 21, 1995 on the advice of then [[Prime Minister of Canada]] [[Jean Chr\u00e9tien]] and sits as a [[Liberal Party of Canada|Liberal]]. In January 2004, she was appointed Government [[parliamentary whip|Whip]] in the Senate, the first woman ever to hold this role. Loisier-Cool left the Senate upon reaching the mandatory retirement age of 75 on June 18, 2012.\n\n==External links==\n* {{Canadian Parliament links|ID=14040}}\n*[http://www.liberalsenateforum.ca/Senator/losier Liberal Senate Forum]\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Losier-Cool, Rose-Marie}}\n[[Category:1937 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Liberal Party of Canada senators]]\n[[Category:Canadian senators from New Brunswick]]\n[[Category:Canadian schoolteachers]]\n[[Category:Women members of the Senate of Canada]]\n[[Category:Women in New Brunswick politics]]\n[[Category:21st-century Canadian politicians]]\n[[Category:21st-century Canadian women politicians]]\n\n\n{{NewBrunswick-politician-stub}}\n", "name_user": "Iridescent", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200etop:Cleanup andtypo fixing,typo(s) fixed: 1994-95 \u2192 1994\u201395", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Rose-Marie_Losier-Cool"}
{"title_page": "Alexander C. DesBrisay", "text_new": "'''Alexander Campbell DesBrisay''' (1828 \u2013 April 8, 1873) was a [[French Canadian]] businessman and politician in the [[New Brunswick|Province of New Brunswick]]. The son of Solomon DesBrisay, and his wife, Mary Campbell, he was a descendant of [[Th\u00e9ophile de la Cour DesBrisay|Captain Th\u00e9ophile de la Cour DesBrisay]] (1671\u20131761) whose [[Huguenot]] family fled religious persecution in [[France]] and settled in [[Dublin]], [[Ireland]] before emigrating to Canada.\n\nAlexander DesBrisay was born in [[Bedeque,Prince Edward Island]] and educated at a public school. As an adult, he was a successful businessman in both the [[lumber]] and [[fishing]] industries. He married Janet Finnis with whom he had six sons and three daughters.\n\nA supporter of the Province of New Brunswick joining the proposed [[Canadian Confederation]], in the February 21, 1865 [[1865 New Brunswick general election|New Brunswick general election]], DesBrisay was voted into office as the [[Confederation Party]] representative for [[Restigouche County, New Brunswick|Restigouche County]] in an   election won by an [[Anti-Confederation Party]] made up of a coalition of [[Progressive Conservative Party of New Brunswick|Conservatives]] and [[Reform movement (pre-Confederation Canada)|Reformers]] led by [[Albert J. Smith]].\n\nDesBrisay was reelected in the [[1866 New Brunswick general election]] won by his party. On August 16, 1867, [[Premier of New Brunswick|Premier]] [[Andrew Rainsford Wetmore|Andrew Wetmore]] appointed him to the [[Executive Council of New Brunswick|Cabinet]] as a [[Minister without Portfolio]]. He held this appointment until May 25, 1870, when the Administration was re-organized under the leadership of the new [[Liberal-Conservative Party]] Premier, [[George Edwin King|George E. King]].\n\nHe was returned to office again in the [[1870 New Brunswick general election|1870 provincial election]]. That fall he resigned his seat in order to run in the November 25 Federal [[by-election]] for a seat in the [[House of Commons of Canada]] for the [[Restigouche (electoral district)|constituency of Restigouche]] to replace [[William Murray Caldwell]] who had died in office. Unsuccessful in his bid for federal office, DesBrisay returned to private business but died a few years later from [[smallpox]] at [[Dalhousie, New Brunswick]]. He is buried in the Presbyterian Church Cemetery in Bathurst.\n\n==References==\n* [http://www.islandregister.com/desbrisay1.html Genealogy of Alexander DesBrisay]\n\n*\"Prince Edward Island Baptism Card Index, 1721-1885,\" database with images, FamilySearch (https://familysearch.org/ark:/61903/1:1:KCXD-96L : 11 March 2018), Alexander Campbell Desbrisay, 04 Apr 1829; citing p. 65, volume 1, Richmond, Prince Edward Island, Public Archives, Charlottetown; FHL microfilm 1,487,753.\n\n*\"Find A Grave Index,\" database, FamilySearch (https://familysearch.org/ark:/61903/1:1:QPR3-VV2V : 28 September 2018), Alexander Campbell  DesBrisay, ; Burial, Bathurst, Gloucester, New Brunswick, Canada, Saint Luke's Presbyterian Cemetery; citing record ID 191953461, Find a Grave, http://www.findagrave.com.\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Desbrisay, Alexander C.}}\n[[Category:1828 births]]\n[[Category:1873 deaths]]\n[[Category:Businesspeople from New Brunswick]]\n[[Category:Members of the Legislative Assembly of New Brunswick]]\n[[Category:Members of the Executive Council of New Brunswick]]\n[[Category:New Brunswick candidates for Member of Parliament]]\n[[Category:DesBrisay family|Alexander C]]\n[[Category:Infectious disease deaths in New Brunswick]]\n[[Category:Deaths from smallpox]]\n[[Category:People from Bathurst, New Brunswick]]\n[[Category:Colony of New Brunswick people]]\n\n\n{{NewBrunswick-politician-stub}}\n", "text_old": "'''Alexander Campbell DesBrisay''' (1828 \u2013 April 8, 1873) was a [[French Canadian]] businessman and politician in the [[New Brunswick|Province of New Brunswick]]. The son of Solomon DesBrisay, and his wife, Mary Campbell, he was a descendant of [[Th\u00e9ophile de la Cour DesBrisay|Captain Th\u00e9ophile de la Cour DesBrisay]] (1671\u20131761) whose [[Huguenot]] family fled religious persecution in [[France]] and settled in [[Dublin]], [[Ireland]] before emigrating to Canada.\n\nAlexander DesBrisay was born in [[Bedeque,Prince Edward Island]] and educated at a public school. As an adult, he was a successful businessman in both the [[lumber]] and [[fishing]] industries. He married Janet Finnis with whom he had six sons and three daughters.\n\nA supporter of the Province of New Brunswick joining the proposed [[Canadian Confederation]], in the February 21, 1865 [[1865 New Brunswick general election|New Brunswick general election]], DesBrisay was voted into office as the [[Confederation Party]] representative for [[Restigouche County, New Brunswick|Restigouche County]] in an   election won by an [[Anti-Confederation Party]] made up of a coalition of [[Progressive Conservative Party of New Brunswick|Conservatives]] and [[Reform movement (pre-Confederation Canada)|Reformers]] led by [[Albert J. Smith]].\n\nDesBrisay was reelected in the [[1866 New Brunswick general election]] won by his party. On August 16, 1867, [[Premier of New Brunswick|Premier]] [[Andrew Rainsford Wetmore|Andrew Wetmore]] appointed him to the [[Executive Council of New Brunswick|Cabinet]] as a [[Minister without Portfolio]]. He held this appointment until May 25, 1870, when the Administration was re-organized under the leadership of the new [[Liberal-Conservative Party]] Premier, [[George Edwin King|George E. King]].\n\nHe was returned to office again in the [[1870 New Brunswick general election|1870 provincial election]]. That fall he resigned his seat in order to run in the November 25 Federal [[by-election]] for a seat in the [[House of Commons of Canada]] for the [[Restigouche (electoral district)|constituency of Restigouche]] to replace [[William Murray Caldwell]] who had died in office. Unsuccessful in his bid for federal office, DesBrisay returned to private business but died a few years later from [[smallpox]] at [[Dalhousie, New Brunswick]]. He is buried in the Presbyterian Church Cemetery in Bathurst.\n\n==References==\n* [http://www.islandregister.com/desbrisay1.html Genealogy of Alexander DesBrisay]\n\n*\"Prince Edward Island Baptism Card Index, 1721-1885,\" database with images, FamilySearch (https://familysearch.org/ark:/61903/1:1:KCXD-96L : 11 March 2018), Alexander Campbell Desbrisay, 04 Apr 1829; citing p. 65, volume 1, Richmond , Prince Edward Island, Public Archives, Charlottetown; FHL microfilm 1,487,753.\n\n*\"Find A Grave Index,\" database, FamilySearch (https://familysearch.org/ark:/61903/1:1:QPR3-VV2V : 28 September 2018), Alexander Campbell  DesBrisay, ; Burial, Bathurst, Gloucester, New Brunswick, Canada, Saint Luke's Presbyterian Cemetery; citing record ID 191953461, Find a Grave, http://www.findagrave.com.\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Desbrisay, Alexander C.}}\n[[Category:1828 births]]\n[[Category:1873 deaths]]\n[[Category:Businesspeople from New Brunswick]]\n[[Category:Members of the Legislative Assembly of New Brunswick]]\n[[Category:Members of the Executive Council of New Brunswick]]\n[[Category:New Brunswick candidates for Member of Parliament]]\n[[Category:DesBrisay family|Alexander C]]\n[[Category:Infectious disease deaths in New Brunswick]]\n[[Category:Deaths from smallpox]]\n[[Category:People from Bathurst, New Brunswick]]\n[[Category:Colony of New Brunswick people]]\n\n\n{{NewBrunswick-politician-stub}}\n", "name_user": "Iridescent", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eReferences:Cleanup andtypo fixing,typo(s) fixed: ,  \u2192 ,", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Alexander_C._DesBrisay"}
{"title_page": "Aus der Tiefen rufe ich, Herr, zu dir, BWV 131", "text_new": "{{good article}}\n{{Infobox Bach composition\n| title                 = {{lang|de|Aus der Tiefen rufe ich, Herr, zu dir}}\n| bwv                   = 131\n| image                 = File:Kirche St. Marien - Innenraum.JPG\n| image_upright         = 1.1\n| caption               = The [[Marienkirche, M\u00fchlhausen|Marienkirche]], M\u00fchlhausen, whose minister commissioned the cantata\n| type                  = [[Church cantata (Bach)|Church cantata]]\n| composed              = {{Timeline-event|date={{Start date|1707}}?|location=[[M\u00fchlhausen]]}}\n| movements             = 5\n| bible                 = {{Sourcetext|source=Bible|version=King James|book=Psalms|chapter=130}}\n| chorale               = \"[[Herr Jesu Christ, du h\u00f6chstes Gut]]\" by [[Bartholom\u00e4us Ringwaldt]]\n| vocal                 = {{plainlist|\n* [[SATB|{{abbr|SATB|soprano, alto, tenor and bass}}]] choir\n* tenor and bass solo\n}}\n| instrumental          = {{hlist | oboe | bassoon | violin | 2 violas | continuo }}\n| italic title = no\n}}\n'''{{lang|de|Aus der Tiefen rufe ich, Herr, zu dir}}''' (Out of the depths I call, Lord, to You),<ref name=\"Dellal\">{{cite web\n| last = Dellal\n| first = Pamela\n| authorlink = Pamela Dellal\n| url = http://www.emmanuelmusic.org/notes_trans/transl_cantata/bwv131.htm\n| title = BWV 131 \u2013 Aus der Tiefen rufe ich, Herr, zu dir\n| publisher = [[Emmanuel Music]]\n| accessdate = 26 March 2016\n}}</ref> '''{{nowrap|BWV 131}}''',{{efn|\"BWV\" is [[Bach-Werke-Verzeichnis]], a thematic catalogue of Bach's works.}} is a [[Bach cantata|church cantata]] by the German composer [[Johann Sebastian Bach]]. It was composed in either 1707 or 1708, which makes it one of [[Early cantata (Bach)|Bach's earliest cantatas]]. Some sources suggest that it could be his earliest surviving work in this form, but current thinking is that there are one or two earlier examples.\n\nThe cantata was commissioned by the minister of one of the churches in [[M\u00fchlhausen]], the city where Bach worked at the time. It was possibly written for a special occasion. The text is based on [[Martin Luther|Luther]]'s German version of [[Psalm 130]] and also incorporates the words of a [[chorale]]. Bach's music integrates melodies from the chorale into larger structures. Bach also shows his interest in [[counterpoint]], something which was characteristic of him throughout his career.\n\n== History and words ==\n\nA note on the [[autograph]] score of the cantata indicates that the work was commissioned by Georg Christian Eilmar, minister of the [[St. Mary's Church, M\u00fchlhausen|Marienkirche]] (St. Mary's church) in [[M\u00fchlhausen]].  This allows the work to be dated to 1707\u201308, which is the period when Bach was living in M\u00fchlhausen.  Bach was employed as organist at the city's other main church, [[Divi Blasii, M\u00fchlhausen|Divi Blasii]],.{{sfn|Wolff|2002|p=104}} He was also involved to some extent with performances at the Marienkirche, where civic ceremonies were held.  One service there which Bach would have attended was that for the city council's inauguration in 1708 during which his cantata [[Gott ist mein K\u00f6nig, BWV 71|''Gott ist mein Konig'', BWV 71]] had its premiere. He may have had a closer personal relationship with Eilmar than with the minister of his own church. Eilmar was godfather to his daughter Catharina Dorothea (born 1708).{{sfn|Wolff|2002|p=112}}\n\n{{lang|de|Aus der Tiefen rufe ich, Herr, zu dir}} has been described as possibly Bach's first surviving cantata.<ref name=\"Oxford\">{{cite web | url=http://www.oxfordmusiconline.com/subscriber/article/opr/t114/e522 | title=Bach, Johann Sebastian | publisher=[[Oxford Music Online]] (subscription access) | work=[[The Oxford Companion to Music]].  Ed. Alison Latham | accessdate=August 3, 2009 | author=Smallman, Basil}}</ref><ref name=\"Washington post\">{{cite web | url=http://www.highbeam.com/doc/1P2-938087.html | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140610214715/http://www.highbeam.com/doc/1P2-938087.html | url-status=dead | archive-date=June 10, 2014 | title=For Bach's Birthday, the Soloists' Joyful Celebration | work=[[The Washington Post]]|publisher=[[HighBeam Research]] (subscription access) | date=March 21, 1993 | accessdate=August 30, 2012 | author=McLellan, Joseph}}</ref>  For it to be the first, it has to be assumed not only that it predates other cantatas written in M\u00fchlhausen (we know that he wrote at least one other there), but also that there is not a surviving cantata from his previous post at [[Arnstadt]]. It seems likely that Bach was composing choral music at Arnstadt. Although Bach was only 22 when he took up the appointment at M\u00fchlhausen, the performance of a work of his own composition appears to have been part of the selection process.{{sfn|Geck|2006|p=64}}  Recent scholarship suggests that another surviving cantata [[Nach dir, Herr, verlanget mich, BWV 150|''Nach dir, Herr, verlanget mich'', BWV 150]] could have been composed at Arnstadt.<ref name=\"Isoyama\">{{cite web | last = Isoyama | first = Tadashi | url = http://www.bach-cantatas.com/Pic-Rec-BIG/Suzuki-C01a%5BBIS-CD751%5D.pdf   | title = Cantata No. 150 Nach dir, Herr, verlanget mich (BWV 150) | publisher = Bach-Cantatas | year = 1995 | page = 7 | accessdate = 26 January 2016 }}</ref>\n\nThe [[libretto]] is based on [[Psalm 130]], one of the [[penitential psalms]].  The [[incipit]] of the psalm, \"[[Aus der Tiefen rufe ich, Herr, zu dir]]\", gives the cantata its name.<ref name=\"bachcantatascom\" /> Originally a Hebrew text, the incipit has variants in translation. While {{Sourcetext|source=Bible|version=King James|book=Psalms|chapter=130|verse=1|range=\u20136}} is rendered \"Out of the depths...\" in the English [[King James version]], a closer translation of the German text used by Bach would be \"deep\" rather than \"depths\". The anonymous librettist, possibly Eilmar,<ref name=\"Vermont\">{{cite web | url=http://www.uvm.edu/~classics/faculty/bach/BWV131.html | title=BWV 131 Aus der Tiefen rufe ich, Herr, zu dir | publisher=[[University of Vermont]] | accessdate=September 19, 2012 | author=Ambrose, Z. Philip}}</ref> includes in two of the movements verses from \"{{lang|de|[[Herr Jesu Christ, du h\u00f6chstes Gut]]|italic=no}}\", a [[Lutheran hymn]] by [[Bartholom\u00e4us Ringwaldt]]. The hymn is also penitential. Bach later used it as the basis for the cantata {{lang|de|[[Herr Jesu Christ, du h\u00f6chstes Gut, BWV 113|''Herr Jesu Christ, du h\u00f6chstes Gut'', BWV 113]]|italic=unset}}, where the words form a counterpart to the tax collector's prayer in the parable of the [[Pharisee and the Publican]], the [[Gospel (liturgy)|gospel reading]] for the eleventh Sunday after [[Trinity Sunday|Trinity]].\n\nIn his [[Bach Cantata Pilgrimage]], Sir [[John Eliot Gardiner]] performed and recorded the work with cantatas for the Fifth Sunday after [[Trinity Sunday|Trinity]],<ref name=cantatafinder>This was partly for a practical reason, the paucity of surviving cantatas for that particular Sunday. See [http://www.cantatafinder.com/ Cantatafinder] \u2013 search tool dedicated to the live recordings made during the Bach Cantata Pilgrimage under the [[Soli Deo Gloria (record label)|SDG]] label</ref> but it is not known for sure when in the [[liturgical year]] Bach performed it, and there has been speculation that it was written for a special occasion.<ref name=\"bachcantatascom\">{{cite web |url=http://www.bach-cantatas.com/Texts/BWV131-Eng3.htm |title=Aus der Tiefen rufe ich, Herr, zu dir, BWV 131 |website=Bach-Cantatas.com |access-date=September 7, 2012}} (information based on [[Alfred D\u00fcrr|D\u00fcrr]], ''Die Kantaten'' and the ''[[Oxford Companions|Oxford Composer Companion: J.S.Bach]]'')</ref>\n\n=== Publication ===\nBach's ability as a composer was recognised by the city council of Muhlhausen who paid for the printing of the cantata ''Gott ist mein Konig'', BWV 71.<ref>[[Johann Sebastian Bach|Bach, Johann Sebastian]]: [http://digital.staatsbibliothek-berlin.de/werkansicht/?PPN=PPN835047814 ''Gl\u00fcckw\u00fcnschende Kirchen Motetto, als bey solennen Gottesdienste in ...''] [[M\u00fchlhausen]]: Tobias David Br\u00fcckner, 1708 ([http://www.bachdigital.de/receive/BachDigitalSource_source_00000615 D-B Mus. 11495]: original print at [[Berlin State Library]])</ref>\nThey may also have arranged the publication of a later cantata now lost. None of the other cantatas was published in the composer's lifetime.\n{{lang|de|Aus der Tiefen rufe ich, Herr, zu dir}} was first published in 1881 as part of the [[Bach-Gesellschaft-Ausgabe]], the first complete edition of Bach's works.<ref name=\"IMSLP\">{{IMSLP2|work=Aus der Tiefe rufe ich, Herr, zu dir, BWV 131 (Bach, Johann Sebastian)|cname=Aus der Tiefe rufe ich, Herr, zu dir, BWV 131}}</ref> The editor was [[Wilhelm Rust]],<ref name=\"IMSLP\" /> who edited many volumes for the Bach-Gesellschaft. At the time of publication of this volume, he held the position of [[Thomaskantor]] in Leipzig.\n\n== Scoring and structure ==\n\n=== Singers ===\nBach scored the work for [[tenor]] and [[Bass (voice type)|bass]] soloists and a four-part choir.  Bach gives his soloists an [[arioso]] and an [[aria]].<ref name=\"bachcantatascom\" /> As in other early cantatas, there are no [[recitatives]]. (Bach later came more under the influence of Italian music, combining recitatives and arias).<ref name=\"emmanuel\" />\n\nBach did not give a direct indication of how many singers he envisaged in the choir.  The cantata can be performed with only four singers, as in the recording by [[Joshua Rifkin]], who is well known in the world of Bach performance for his \"[[OVPP|one voice to a part]]\" approach. However, most recordings feature a choir with multiple voices to a part.  Another choice to be made is whether to use women singers: Bach's original singers were probably all male.<ref name=\"Women\">{{cite web | url=http://ism.yale.edu/event/conference-womens-influence-js-bachs-music | title=Considering Women's Impact on the Music of Johann Sebastian Bach | publisher=[[Yale Institute of Sacred Music]] | accessdate=March 30, 2016}}</ref>  Most recordings of the cantata, however, feature mixed choirs: an exception is the version conducted by [[Nikolaus Harnoncourt]], which deploys boys' voices as the top lines of the choir.<ref>Recorded in 1981,[http://www.bach-cantatas.com/Performers/H&L-Rec6.htm#L32] this version is part of a [[Bach cantatas (Teldec)|complete set of the cantatas]], a joint project with [[Gustav Leonhardt]], which mainly uses male voices.</ref>\n\n=== Instruments ===\nThe singers are accompanied by an [[Baroque instruments|instrumental group]] consisting of [[oboe]], [[bassoon]], [[violin]], two [[viola]]s and [[basso continuo]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://webdocs.cs.ualberta.ca/~wfb/cantatas/131.html|accessdate=30 May 2014|publisher=University of Alberta|title=BWV 131}}</ref> As in the case of the singers, the question arises as to whether Bach used one or more players per part. The oboe and the violin are given some important solos, suggesting that there may well have been only one of each. [[Ton Koopman]], for example, uses one oboist and one violinist in his recording. The role of the violas is more to provide [[accompaniment]], filling in harmonies and sometimes doubling vocal lines. The bassoon sometimes supports the continuo section, doubling its bass line, and sometimes plays an independent line.<ref name=\"emmanuel\">{{cite web | url=http://www.emmanuelmusic.org/notes_translations/notes_cantata/n_bwv131.htm | title=Cantata 131; Programme Notes | publisher=[[Emmanuel Music]] | accessdate=September 3, 2012 | author=Smith, Craig}}</ref>\n\n=== Musical forms ===\n[[File:Young Bach2.jpg|thumb|upright|alt=disputed portrait of the young Bach, with brown curled hair, dressed festively|Portrait of the young Bach (disputed)<ref>{{cite web|last=Towe|first=Teri Noel|title=The Portrait in Erfurt Alleged to Depict Bach, the Weimar Concertmeister|work=The Face Of Bach|url=http://www.npj.com/thefaceofbach/09w624.html|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110716074347/http://www.npj.com/thefaceofbach/09w624.html|archivedate=16 July 2011|accessdate=28 April 2014}}</ref>]]\nBach used some musical forms which reappear in later cantatas.  For example, two of the choral movements have a [[fugue]], a style of composition in which Bach excelled. Also, the two movements for soloists are developed as a type of [[chorale fantasia]] with the soloist singing the psalm text and an upper voice singing the chorale in long notes as a [[cantus firmus]].<ref name=\"Mincham\">{{cite web | url=http://www.jsbachcantatas.com/documents/chapter-64-bwv-131.htm | title=Chapter 64 BWV 131 Aus der Tiefen rufe ich, Herr, zu dir | publisher=jsbachcantatas.com | date=December 2010 | accessdate=September 17, 2012 | author=Mincham, Julian}}</ref>   [[Craig Smith (conductor)|Craig Smith]] called the chorale settings \"a window on the future\". However, he criticised the structure of the cantata, saying that it offers evidence that at this stage in his career the composer had difficulty with large forms.<ref name=\"emmanuel\" /> On the other hand, the musicologist Julian Mincham regards the piece as being different from later cantatas rather than inferior to them.<ref name=\"Mincham\" />\n\n=== Structure and scoring ===\nBach structured the cantata in five movements, three choral movements interspersed by an [[arioso]] and an [[aria]]. In both solo movements, a chorale stanza sung simultaneously by the soprano intensifies the Psalm text. He scored it for two soloist ([[tenor]] and [[Bass (voice type)|bass]]), a [[SATB|four-part choir]], and a small [[Baroque instruments|Baroque instrumental ensemble]] of [[oboe]] (Ob), [[bassoon]] (Fg),  [[violin]] (Vl), two [[viola]]s (Va), and [[basso continuo]].<ref name=\"Bischof\">{{cite web  | last = Bischof  | first = Walter F.  | url = http://webdocs.cs.ualberta.ca/~wfb/cantatas/131.html  | title = BWV 150 Aus der Tiefen rufe ich, Herr, zu dir | publisher = University of Alberta | accessdate = 25 March 2013}}</ref>\n\nIn the following table of the movements, the scoring follows the [[New Bach Edition]] (''Neue Bach-Ausgabe'').<ref name=\"Bischof\" /> The [[Key (music)|keys]] and [[time signature]]s are taken from [[Alfred D\u00fcrr]],{{sfn|D\u00fcrr|2006|p=}} using the symbol [[File:Commontime inline.png|11px]] for [[common time]] (4/4). The continuo, playing throughout, is not shown.\n{{Classical movement header | show_text_source = yes | work = {{lang|de|Aus der Tiefen rufe ich, Herr, zu dir}}, BWV 131 | instruments1 = Winds | instruments2 = Strings }}\n\n{{Classical movement row\n| id = m1\n| number = [[#1|1]]\n| title = {{lang|de|Aus der Tiefen rufe ich, Herr, zu dir}}\n| text_source = {{nowrap|Ps. 130:1\u20132}}\n| type = Chorus\n| vocal = SATB\n| instruments1 = Ob Fg\n| instruments2 = Vl 2Va\n| key = {{nowrap|[[G minor]]}}\n| time = {{hlist| 3/4 | {{music|common-time}}\n}}\n}}\n{{Classical movement row\n| id = m2\n| number = [[#2|2]]\n| title = {{lang|de|So du willst, Herr, S\u00fcnde zurechnen}}\n| text_source = {{plainlist|\n* Ps. 130:3\u20134\n* Ringwaldt\n}}\n| type = Arioso e chorale\n| vocal = {{plainlist|\n* B\n* S\n}}\n| instruments1 = Ob\n| instruments2 = \n| key ={{nowrap|[[G minor]]}} \n| time ={{music|common-time}} \n}}\n{{Classical movement row\n| id = m3\n| number = [[#3|3]]\n| title = {{lang|de|Ich harre des Herrn, meine Seele harret}}\n| text_source = Ps. 130:5\n| type = Chorus\n| vocal = SATB\n| instruments1 = Ob Fg\n| instruments2 = Vl 2Va\n| key = {{plainlist|\n* [[E\u266d major]]\n* [[G minor]]\n}} \n| time = {{music|common-time}}\n}}\n{{Classical movement row\n| id = m4\n| number = [[#4|4]]\n| title = {{lang|de|Meine Seele wartet auf den Herrn von einer Morgenwache}}''\n| text_source = {{plainlist|\n* Ps. 130:6\n* Ringwaldt\n}}\n| type = Aria e chorale\n| vocal = {{plainlist|\n* T\n* A\n}}\n| instruments1 = \n| instruments2 = \n| key = {{nowrap|[[C minor]]}}\n| time = 12/8\n}}\n{{Classical movement row\n| id = m5\n| number = [[#5|5]]\n| title = {{lang|de|Israel hoffe auf den Herrn; denn bei dem Herrn}}\n| text_source = {{nowrap|Ps. 130:7\u20138}}\n| type = Chorus\n| vocal = SATB\n| instruments1 = Ob Fg\n| instruments2 = Vl 2Va\n| key = {{nowrap|[[G minor]]}}\n| time = {{music|common-time}}\n}}\n\n{{End}}\n\n== Recordings ==\nThe following entries are taken from the listing on the Bach Cantatas Website.<ref name=\"Oron\">{{cite web\n| last = Oron\n| first = Aryeh\n| url = http://www.bach-cantatas.com/BWV131.htm\n| title = Cantata BWV 131 Aus der Tiefen rufe ich, Herr, zu dir\n| publisher = Bach-Cantatas\n| accessdate = 26 March 2016\n}}</ref> Choirs with one voice per part (OVPP) and ensembles playing period instruments in [[historically informed performance]]s are marked by green background.\n\n{{Cantata discography header|work={{lang|de|Aus der Tiefen rufe ich, Herr, zu dir}}, BWV 131 | show_choir_type=yes | instruments={{abbr|Instr.|Type of instruments}}}}\n\n{{Cantata discography row\n| id = Shaw\n| title = ''J. S. Bach: Cantatas BWV 131 & BWV 140''\n| conductor = {{sortname|Robert|Shaw|dab=conductor}}\n| choir = [[Robert Shaw Chorale]]\n| orchestra = [[RCA Victor Orchestra]]\n| soloists = {{plainlist|\n* [[William Hess (tenor)|William Hess]]\n* [[Paul Matthen]]\n}}\n| label = [[RCA]]\n| year = {{Start date|1949}}\n| choir_type = \n| orchestra_type = \n}}\n{{Cantata discography row\n| id = Ramin\n| title = ''Bach Made in Germany Vol. 1 \u2013 Cantatas IX''\n| conductor = {{sortname|G\u00fcnther|Ramin}}\n| choir = [[Thomanerchor]]\n| orchestra = [[Gewandhausorchester]]\n| soloists = {{plainlist|\n* [[Gert Lutze]]\n* [[Johannes Oettel]]\n}}\n| label = Eterna\n| year = {{Start date|1952}}\n| choir_type = \n| orchestra_type = \n}}\n{{Cantata discography row\n| id = Werner\